WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.800
Hello, and welcome to this case study, Mortgage Trading Analysis in Power BI.

2
00:00:06.800 --> 00:00:11.360
My name is Nick Edwards, and I am very excited to be your instructor.

3
00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:16.160
In this case study, you will learn about the financial system hands-on as you play

4
00:00:16.160 --> 00:00:22.760
the part of a Junior Trader at a fictional non-bank mortgage lender, Sooper Mortgage.

5
00:00:22.760 --> 00:00:28.000
Mortgage markets are similar globally, but this case study will be based on the U.S.

6
00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:29.400
markets.

7
00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:34.320
Your objective is to execute a trade of mortgages in the capital markets by

8
00:00:34.320 --> 00:00:41.080
analyzing mortgage data, market prices, and Sooper Mortgage's target profit on the trade.

9
00:00:41.080 --> 00:00:49.240
The date is September 21st, 2021, and the trade will settle on October 13th, 2021.

10
00:00:49.240 --> 00:00:55.680
The datasets in this course describe a population of over 5,000 mortgages, and it derives from

11
00:00:55.680 --> 00:01:03.440
real mortgage and financial market data, although they have been altered and simplified for this course.

12
00:01:03.440 --> 00:01:07.160
This is an intermediate-advanced course, so you will have an

13
00:01:07.160 --> 00:01:12.000
opportunity to test your skills and apply them to complex problems.

14
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:14.800
By the end of this course, you will be confident with new

15
00:01:14.800 --> 00:01:19.440
skills and strategies that you can bring with you into the real world.

16
00:01:19.440 --> 00:01:25.360
You should be comfortable writing DAX code, a bit of M, and understand the Power Query Editor.

17
00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:30.920
Therefore, we recommend you take these courses before starting this case study.

18
00:01:30.920 --> 00:01:37.080
If you're unsure, stick around, try a few exercises, and use the hints available.

19
00:01:37.080 --> 00:01:41.520
Finally, it's okay if you don't have any financial background.

20
00:01:41.520 --> 00:01:46.120
You will find this course engaging as you learn about the financial system.

21
00:01:46.120 --> 00:01:49.160
Okay, let's get into the content.

22
00:01:49.160 --> 00:01:55.320
Perhaps you find yourself asking what the financial system is and how trading mortgages fit into it.

23
00:01:55.320 --> 00:01:56.840
It's a great question.

24
00:01:56.840 --> 00:02:01.920
A financial system is a collective group of people, banks, financial

25
00:02:01.920 --> 00:02:08.000
institutions, and lenders working together to move money around in the economy!

26
00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:14.560
People with extra money will save or invest their money with banks and financial institutions.

27
00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:17.200
We call these people "savers".

28
00:02:17.200 --> 00:02:20.520
Savers do this because they expect the bank or financial

29
00:02:20.520 --> 00:02:24.160
institution to keep their money safe and earn interest over time.

30
00:02:24.160 --> 00:02:28.080
People who need extra money go to lenders.

31
00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:30.160
They are called borrowers.

32
00:02:30.160 --> 00:02:36.640
In exchange for money, borrowers will sign a loan agreement for the lender and pay some fees.

33
00:02:36.640 --> 00:02:44.120
A loan agreement is a promise to repay the borrowed loan amount, usually with interest, in monthly payments.

34
00:02:44.120 --> 00:02:49.880
Lenders are happy to write loan agreements because they make money on the fees they charge to the borrowers.

35
00:02:49.880 --> 00:02:55.560
But, for example, when they lend $100,000, where do they get this money.

36
00:02:55.560 --> 00:03:01.960
Lenders get their money by selling their loans in the capital markets to banks or financial institutions?

37
00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:08.600
When they do this, the lender will have the money again to write more loans and continue earning fees.

38
00:03:08.600 --> 00:03:14.880
Our case study will focus on this part as we trade mortgage loans to financial institutions.

39
00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:21.120
Note that some banks also act as lenders, so this step is not always necessary.

40
00:03:21.120 --> 00:03:27.120
Banks and financial institutions are happy to purchase loan agreements because they see the

41
00:03:27.120 --> 00:03:33.320
loan as an investment that earns interest over time with each monthly payment the borrower makes.

42
00:03:33.320 --> 00:03:43.760
For example, a 30-year $100,000 loan with a 5% annual interest rate will pay $195,000 in total.

43
00:03:43.760 --> 00:03:47.960
That's $95,000 in interest earned for the investor.

44
00:03:47.960 --> 00:03:53.120
Some interest earned from the investments is also returned to the savers!

45
00:03:53.120 --> 00:03:54.080
And there we are.

46
00:03:54.080 --> 00:03:55.480
We've come full circle!

47
00:03:55.480 --> 00:03:59.440
This is a simplified version of the financial system.

48
00:03:59.440 --> 00:04:06.240
In reality, it is much more complex, with thousands of banks, lenders, and billions of people.

49
00:04:06.240 --> 00:04:10.840
This system is so intertwined that if you owe any debt, you may

50
00:04:10.840 --> 00:04:14.920
indirectly own a small fraction of it in your own investment account!

51
00:04:14.920 --> 00:04:19.200
So a healthy financial system is key to a great economy.

52
00:04:19.200 --> 00:04:22.800
We'll continue to explore this in more detail throughout the course.

53
00:04:22.800 --> 00:04:27.120
For now, let's put these concepts to use.

54
00:04:27.120 --> 00:04:27.160
.

